<section id="summer-camp" class="slide">
  <header class="slide-header">
    <p class="eyebrow">Adjacent topic</p>
    <h2>Summer camp accounts — a concrete test of the policy framework</h2>
    <p class="subhead">The decisions above are not theoretical. The first cohort to exercise them is the summer-camp roster being provisioned in the next few weeks.</p>
  </header>

  <h3>Why this belongs in this conversation</h3>
  <p>Provisioning summer-camp students is a smaller, cleaner version of every structural finding in this audit. A bounded cohort with a known start date, known end date, no FERPA-record history to migrate, and explicit parental consent at the front. If the off-boarding rule, the OU structure, and the AI-tooling policy are answered for camp, they are answered in principle for the school year that follows.</p>

  <h3>The proposed structure</h3>
  <ul class="kv">
    <li><span class="k">Domain</span><span class="v">@springfieldca.org (same as school)</span></li>
    <li><span class="k">Organizational unit</span><span class="v">/Summer Camp 2026</span></li>
    <li><span class="k">Provisioning</span><span class="v">GAM batch from CSV roster</span></li>
    <li><span class="k">Lifecycle</span><span class="v">Auto-suspend day +1 after camp ends; delete day +90</span></li>
    <li><span class="k">Drive content</span><span class="v">Archived to a designated retention account before suspension</span></li>
    <li><span class="k">Parental consent</span><span class="v">One document per family, names the AI tools explicitly</span></li>
  </ul>
  <p class="caption">Putting the cohort in its own organizational unit means policies (Drive sharing, Gmail external send, AI tool access) can apply to the whole group at once and the entire OU can be suspended in a single action when camp ends. This is the operational pattern that today's audit is recommending for the school as a whole — camp lets us pilot it first.</p>

  <h3>The decision underneath — AI access via school accounts vs. personal accounts</h3>
  <p>One question is large enough that it should land in front of you as a direct comparison. Where do the AI tools the campers will use (Gemini, NotebookLM) actually live?</p>

  <table class="recon">
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th scope="col">Dimension</th>
        <th scope="col">School-managed accounts</th>
        <th scope="col">Personal Google accounts</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><strong>Direct cost to the school</strong></td><td>AI add-on or Education Plus license per camper</td><td>$0</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Eligibility for under-18</strong></td><td>Admin-controlled. Workspace under-18 policy applies — needs verification before commit.</td><td>Restricted. Many AI features are blocked on personal accounts for users under 18 even with parental consent.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Use of student work to train AI models</strong></td><td>Prohibited by Workspace contract terms.</td><td>Permitted under consumer ToS. Student work may be retained and used.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>FERPA / education-record protection</strong></td><td>School holds and controls records under existing framework.</td><td>No school control. Records held by Google under consumer terms.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Audit and incident response</strong></td><td>Admin Console logs every action. School can investigate any complaint.</td><td>School has no visibility. Cannot help and cannot prove compliance.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Instructor feedback on student work</strong></td><td>Possible — student work is in shared school environment.</td><td>Not possible at scale. Each student is in a personal silo.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Operational support during camp</strong></td><td>School IT can reset passwords, recover access, transfer files.</td><td>School cannot. Account recovery goes through the family.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>What happens to student work after camp</strong></td><td>Archived under defined retention policy.</td><td>Disappears if family deletes the account. Persists indefinitely under Google's profile if they don't.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Real liability to the school</strong></td><td>School is operating the camp and holds the tools and records to manage that responsibility.</td><td>School is still operating the camp. "Personal accounts" is not a recognized defense — operational authority is the locus, not domain.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <aside class="callout recommendation">
    <p><strong>Recommendation.</strong> School-managed accounts in <code>/Summer Camp 2026</code>, scoped to free Fundamentals plus the specific AI add-ons the curriculum requires. The cost is real but bounded — and can be costed into the camp tuition or eaten as a marketing investment. The protection difference is structural and not recoverable by being careful at run-time.</p>
    <p>The personal-accounts approach trades a visible cost line for a set of invisible structural exposures that are harder to argue about after something goes wrong. The school is operating the program either way.</p>
  </aside>

  <h3>What needs to happen before any of this is committed to parents</h3>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Verify under-18 Gemini and NotebookLM availability</strong> on one provisioned test account in <code>/Summer Camp 2026</code>. Ten minutes of admin-console work. Settles the eligibility question definitively before marketing materials go out.</li>
    <li><strong>Draft the parental consent template</strong> that explicitly names the AI tools, the data flows, the retention policy, and the account deletion date. This is the long-pole item — legal review takes longer than the technical provisioning.</li>
    <li><strong>Finalize the naming convention</strong> for the OU and account format so the provisioning script, the consent form, and the camp roster all align.</li>
  </ol>
  <p>Once those three items are settled, the actual account creation is a couple of hours of <code>gam csv</code> work and the cohort can be rolled on demand.</p>
</section>

